SeismoCloud è una rete comunitaria per la rilevazione dei terremoti e per l'invio di Early Warning, ovvero di avvisi che precedono (di alcuni secondi) l'arrivo di una scossa sismica. La rete funziona grazie a sismometri a basso costo sia fissi, costruiti come dispositivi dedicati, sia mobili, cioè basati su app per smartphone grazie all'uso dei sensori presenti nei dispositivi cellulari. Ogni persona può contribuire alla rilevazione dei terremoti installando l'app o montando e installando a casa un sismometro fisso.

SeismoCloud è un progetto congiunto di ricercatori dell'Università La Sapienza (Dipartimento di Informatica) e dell'Istituto Nazionale di Geofisica e Vulcanologia (Sezione Sismologia e Tettonofisica).

Maggiori informazioni: http://www.seismocloud.com

IL MIO CONTRIBUTO:
Ho realizzato una prima versione del contenitore per l'elettronica per un sismometro fisso.
L'ho realizzato per il mio sismometro, ma potrebbe interessare qualcun altro quindi condivido il progetto.
Il contenitore serve a contenere il modulo ESP8266 (ESP12E), il modulo sensori MPU6050 ed i tre led di stato (0,5mm).
I moduli elettronici in vendita possono avere misure leggermente diverse, ho realizzato il contenitore in modo da poter alloggiare anche i moduli più grandi. Bisogna fissarli all'interno con un po' di colla a caldo.

title: Wall mount for violin/viola and bow

description.text:
This is a wall mount for a viola or violin, and bow. I already had a mount for my guitar and my wife thought it would be nice to mount her viola in a similar way. This is the fourth iteration of my design and it's working perfectly!

Because it's printed in PLA it's a bit slippery so the viola can slide off quite easily. One way to solve this is to glue a small patch of anti-slip material on the spot where the mount and viola meet. Another way, what we ended up doing, is putting a nice rubber band over the two extremities of the mount. This has been working fine for quite a while now.

The model is more than strong enough, I tried to break some early prints and it took quite some force. And these were printed with 20% infill, the final version was printed with 30% infill just to be sure. Print with supports by the way, just for the shoulders of the "u" shape coming out of the base.

Let me know if you like the model, it's my first "thing" here on Thingiverse and also my first "complicated" model in Fusion360 so I'm happy with your feedback!

description.text:
Installing panels at home using countersunk screws, I'm normally using premade plastic 'button-heads' to cover the screw heads once installed. However, my local Bauhaus failed to have the correct size on shelf, meaning I had to think for myself...
So, without further ado, I bring you custom designed button-thingies to click into the torx of eg screws used for securing panelling. In my case the screws were 5*70 T20 - but as I am also providing the sourcecode for OpenSCAD, you are free to adapt them to your personal use. All you need is a vernier caliper, OpenSCAD and time to fiddle.

Printer:

GEEEtech i3 pro B

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2 mm

Infill:

5% or more

I've become addicted to OpenSCAD, as it is simple, provides total control and relies on a process I'm familiar with; textual programming. Here, the output is a 3D-object :)

Designing this thingy required me to either invent something on my own (hard) or copy (easy) the crucial part - the torx. Therefore I've copied a module generating a torx from here.
The rest - the buttonhead itself - is not much to talk about.

Looking over the code (excluding the insanely complex module written by my norwegian muse), you'll find it easy to adapt it to suit your needs - and your printer. With this being something that requires a snug fit to stay in place, you'll have to be prepared for a little experimentation.

title: RC Plane Motor Mount for Turnigy SK3 3542-1250

description.text:
This is an aerodynamic motor mount developed specifically for the Turnigy Aerodrive SK3 3542-1250 for a flying wing pusher. Mounting radius is 34.4 mm (diameter) with 3 mm (diameter) screw holes for motor mounting, screw holes spaced 12.5mm (radius) from the center. Will work with other motors of same mounting dimensions. Note a thrust angle of 5 degrees is included in the design. Point this vector through the CG for proper mounting to your plane. The center of the motor mounting surface is 32.2 mm so you can use that dimension to calculate exactly where the motor mount needs to be placed on the plane.

Note: STL file updated 10/27/17

Let me know what you think! Enjoy

description.text: In the tradition of the Moon Shot and the Earth Shot, This is my shot at making a globe of the 2nd Jovian Galilean moon, Europa.  It is slightly smaller than our moon but is covered in a fractured ice sheet covering a large (presumed) salt water ocean.  It prints perfectly on the Replicator.

Similar to my previous heightfield work with the asteroid Vesta (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:12668)and WilliamAAdamas Moon Shot (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:14011) and EarthShot (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:14070), this is a heightfield mapped on a sphere. I used the enhanced cylindrical map of Europa based on Voyager data (http://solarviews.com/cap/jup/europacyl2.htm) to create a Heightfield in Rhino3D, converted it to a mesh, and used the ApplyMeshUVN command with a value multiplier of 0.1 to map it onto a sphere. (You do this with the math you swore you'd never need again - take the width of the map, divide it by 2*pi and make a sp-here with that radius). Place the sphere centered under the mesh and apply it - except for the poles (which have limited data anyway), the mapping is very good. I did apply a smoothing factor in world coordinates of 0.1 to prevent spikiness. This makes the surface markings subtle but truer to what it actually looks like. Printed on a Replicator using 3 shells, 0.27 layer thickness, 2% infill, exterior support and scaled to match the Moonshot model. Per request, I have uploaded an unsmoothed version (Europaglobefine.stl). I have not printed this yet but the mesh seems fine. If someone beats me to printing it, please upload an image.

Also drilled out the rest of the barrel pieces for running wires to leds or whatever - this will weaken it a little I think, so use extra strong glue.

Added some buttons you can paint/print in white and drop in place - use supports and a brim. Some work will obviously be needed for proper fit. Added a version of the buttons on a sprue for easier painting.

Extended the grip a little - gotta have a place for the pinky to go - maybe specific to Rick's gun?

Tweaked the hammer to reflect an 'armed' position - as seen in some stills. (and tweaked it again)

Shortened the slide a bit, and am tweaking the barrel1 piece (really the body piece where the barrel attaches) so the slide rails aren't visible. I think it'd be pretty easy to to s spring mechanism in there to create the snappy slide action. That is a project for another day, or another thingimixer.

description.text:
This is mainly to stop the filament from carving a groove in the top of the 3d printed spring loaded extruder which you should have printed already as without it it under extrudes. Even if it's printed in abs (which mine is) it will still get worn where the filament goes in. It works with a 695 bearing (do not confuse with 608) what can be found on the inside of some fidget spinners: https://media.licdn.com/mpr/mpr/AAEAAQAAAAAAAAyqAAAAJDMyMmY5ODM2LWQ4MTEtNDRkNy1hZWE5LWUzOTQ2NTliYTU0NQ.jpg
This is compatible with the CTC Prusa i3 pro B fan duct by Jon1h
I took the v-grooved wheel from a random spool holder and resized it.
Pin 1, Pin 3, ctc_fan_ductclip1, vgoovewheel and base .stl are all printed once but Pin 2 is printed twice.
Assembly goes like this: clip the ctc_fan_ductclip1 to the back of the extruder like on the CTC Prusa i3 pro B fan duct by Jon1h
slot the base into the top bit. Insert the 695 bearing into the vgroovewheel (You might need to use a hammer). The assembly of the wheel its self goes like this: (with {} being the holes in the base)

You may want to use a megnetic mount to connect the dock to the car insted of gluing it to your dash like i did.

Blank drink coasters are available from many suppliers including Amazon.com. The bed has little "fingers" that securely hold the coasters without any need for clamping.

Check out the video.
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7_aS0PbP8HY

You can use most 3 axis CAM programs to generate the GCode. You then run the GCode though a pre-processor that converts it to polar coordinates. This allows it to use basic CNC firmware. The firmware thinks it is running a standard 3 axis Cartesian machine.

You can use just any CNC controller that supports at least 2 axes and a servo. I use my pen/laser controller and the base has mounts for it. Other people have used 3D printer controllers like RAMPS.

I have written a few blog post regarding this machine.

  • The Polar Coaster – A Drink Coaster Drawing Machine
  • Polar Pen Machine Kinematics
  • A Polar Pre-Processor for the Pen Bot Written in Python
    Polar Coaster Updates

I printed everything with standard settings on a TAZ 6. The only part that requires support is the radial axis carriage. You can buy the GT2 pulleys or print them. If you are adventurous, you can print the polar belt. I recommend PolyFlex from PolyMaker because it is the least stretchy flex filament I have foound.

title: Prusa i3 MK2 Extruder - Easy hotend access

description.text:
Note: Please check also the newer and more advanced design Articulated part-fan.

The Original Prusa i3 MK2 extruder is a very nice compact design.

However, to change the nozzle, one has to disassemble many of the extruder's parts, removing at least seven screws.

I've made a few changes to the original design, so the part fan and the fan nozzle are now a single unit. They can be easily detached by removing only two screws. The nozzle and the hot-end are then easy to inspect, clean or change.

It fits all the MK2 models: i3 MK2, i3 MK2S and i3 MK2MM.

I suggest to rotate the E3D all-metal hot-end and place it as shown in the images, so the cables are routed directly to the back of the extruder. This will greatly reduce the strain placed onto the cables and will provide a clear view to the hot-end, if someone wants to replace the nozzle. However, it requires to move the heater element and the thermistor to the other side of the hot-end.

After extensive usage and testing of the rotated hot-end placement, I no more support it. Even though it has some advantages, it has a big drawback: it hurts a lot the part cooling. So, I've rotate it back to the original PRUSA design.

description.text:
This is a work-in-progress E3D Chimera/Cyclops mount for the Creality CR-10.
It consists of a two-part mounting plate to fit ontop of the original mounting plate with three of the original M3 screws, the actual holder (one for Chimera/Cyclops and one for the stock hotend), a fan hood for the print cooling fan and two cable buide "claps" either side of the fixture which also adjust the X endstop position for the altered nozzle position.

The mount with the readily assembled heatsink/hotend/nozzle(s) setup slots into the mounting plate an can be secured with two M3x10 screws and two or four M3 nuts which press fit into the respective "sockets".

The "BackMountPlate" can be glued to the "MountWithFanShroud" by use of the also supplied "AllignmentTool" - but should not be required.

In respect to the original hotend the E3D nozzles will be a few millimeters higher, since on my CR-10 the springs are nearly fully compressed already.

This is a filament guide that snaps securely on to popular aluminum extrusions used by a variety of 3D printers. Parts for 2020, 2040 and 3030 extrusions have been included.

I deliberately avoided adding notches to fit into the extrusion channels to avoid compatibility issues between v-slot and t-slot. This design also won't interfere with belts or cables in the channels.

I designed these parts with tight tolerances; 0.1mm on the extrusion dimensions for a tight snap fit and minimal wobble.

If it's too loose, try printing it in Cura (Free) which seems to produce slightly larger perimeters.

description.text: This thing was made with Tinkercad. Edit it online https://www.tinkercad.com/things/bPB8u8RfaMD

A simple, no frills calibration / stress test print.

Print without supports - 'cause that's the point :-)

Overall dimensions are 20mm wide x 40mm long x 30mm high.
The 2 vertical holes are 5 & 3 mm diameter each.
The 1/2 circle along the one side has a diameter of 10mm.
The bridge pillars are 5x5mm, the gap is 5mm and the beams are 5x5mm.
The large arch has a 36mm diameter.

The arch's test your overhangs, and the bridges test your bridging - aka your cooling.
The rest tests basic X/Y/Z calibration and extrusion.

On my machine, at 60mm/s it takes less than 30 minutes to print. At 30mm/s its about an hour.

Neither of my printer / slicer combinations can do it perfectly.

(Ideally the slicer would do perimeters from outside in, unless it detects an overhang > 45 degrees, then do inside out. If possible, never start printing a perimeter on an overhang. And also if possible, start any infill from someplace 'solid', not from the edge of an overhang.)

title: Analogue Nt NES cartridge slot insert

description.text:
This is an insert to fix three problems with the Analogue Nt cartridge slot:

  1. The cart slot is very loose. This removes a lot of the back and forth wiggle.
  2. It raises the cartridge by 3mm. In my experience, the Nt reads carts better if they are slightly raised.
  3. It prevents metal-on-plastic contact with your NES cartridges.

Analogue sent out chintzy little plastic cartridge protectors, but all they do is prevent the metal on plastic contact. The loose cartridge slot is one of the biggest design problems in the Analogue Nt so this is cheap and easy fix.

This was only designed for the original Analogue Nt. I'm not sure if it will fit the Nt mini. It is a tight fit on purpose. If it was made looser, it would come out when you took out the cartridges. I also made a simple dust cover because this holds the cartridge slot open. You might want to make a fancier one.

You might want to sand the curve down after the print so it's smoother. This is probably my favorite thing I've ever made. It vastly improves the Nt in my opinion.

description.text:
This is a bench splicer or in situ splicer for Anet A8.

It is a rework of TrustFm's "Filament Splicer Joiner":
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:977156/#files
The head of the TrustFm's FSJ was used and placed in a C bracket. Make sure to have some M3 nuts and bolts.

The two photos above show the splice helper used on the bench with solvent welding and in situ at the printhead of an Anet A8 for heat welding.

Solvent welding with methylene chloride works, two minute set time and half hour minimum cure time. A bit fussy but it works. $9 gets you a quart of Jasco Premium Paint & Epoxy Remover at the hardware store, it's mostly MeCl2. Here's the MSDS:

http://www.jasco-help.com/uploads/documents/GJBP00203_SDS-4015.34E.pdf

Otherwise, for heat welding, I put aluminum foil on the tip of my soldering iron, set it to 650, and very carefully sculpt a weld. This is a lot faster than solvent welding. I say sculpt because the finished weld must not be wider than the filament and cannot be too narrow or the filament will hang in the wheel and gear and not feed. Any bulge can hang up on the guide hole to the gear and wheel and the spice will break or the gear wheel will grind the filament down and the splice will not move through the hole.

Thanks again to TrustFm's head design! Again, make sure to have 2 M3 nuts and bolts, at least 6mm long, to put in the head. The nuts fit snugly and make sure the hole is cleaned out to dimension, I used an eyeglass flat screwdriver to scrape off the excess filament fluff around, in, down, and at the bottom of the hole.

I really want an in situ splicer at the print head. The difficulty is the filament wants to bend and the two pieces do not want to meet up. You might want to try TrustFm's technique also, it does overcomes the bending problem, and it uses a heat weld.

description.text:
A display that slips over the filament sensor and provides a digital readout of the width in millimeters. This can be used for 3D printers that do not have LCD displays, or if you do not (or can not) interface the sensor directly to the printer.

I also included a new sensor case, with a better light tower design.

Parts needed:

  • filament width sensor see http://objectswithintelligence.weebly.com/
  • 3 wire voltage display (0-30v input), (0-5v supply) from ebay (see picture)
  • USB cable - can recycle one with a micro USB that no longer charges
    *USB charger - to supply sensor power
  • small cable tie
  • printed part: LED Panel Voltmeter Case v2.stl

Optional:
Print out all the .stl files to replace the sensor case with the more streamlined tower design. You will need to attach the tower to the top plate with cyanoacrylates adhesive (superglue) for PLA. Also don't forget to pain the inside of the tower with flat black craft paint.

Construction steps (not wired to printer controller board)
  1. Cut off the micro connector from the USB cable and strip the end so that 1.5 inches of wire is available.
  2. Strip the red and black wire so that they can enter the terminal blocks to power the sensor. The other wires are not used.
  3. Connect the red USB wire and the red wire from the voltmeter display to the senor terminal labeled "+5v"
  4. Connect the black USB wire and the black wire from the voltmeter display to the sensor terminal labeled "gnd"
  5. Connect the remaining white wire from the voltmeter display to the sensor terminal labeled "out".
  6. Press the voltmeter display into the 3D printed part. A friction fit holds the display in place.
  7. Wrap any wires inside the part around the pillars.
  8. Test fit the part by sliding it over the sensor case.
  9. Use a zip tie to hold the USB wire in place - see the picture of the back side.

Optional
Print out a new sensor case to take advantage of the new streamlined tower design. Glue the tower to the sensor top plate using Cyanoacrylate adhesive (super glue). Also be sure to paint the inside of the tower with flat black craft paint.

title: Z Axis Cable Chain for Anet A8

description.text:
I designed this Z axis drag chain to work with the X axis chain that was designed by TNS (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2105040), and the Electronics Case designed by Lindkj (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2294191). The chain links have two options: 16 Links of either the closed chain links designed by sukhoi27 (http://www.thingiverse.com/sukhoi27), or the open chain links closed by zip ties, designed by Starwhooper (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1905344).

When printing the Electronics Case Mount rotate it 90° in the Y direction so that the tabs for attaching the chain links are printed stronger and less likely to break off. Use supports from the build plate and extra cooling when bridging.

The Motor Mount should be printed the way it drops onto the build plate using supports. This orientation also prints strong tabs.

You will need to drill 2 holes large enough for M3 screws in the top of your Electronics Case to attach the Electronics Case Mount. Center the mount between the tab slots with it touching the USB connector. This position should line it up with the cut out on the Electronics Case Cover, and allow the cover to be removable without the electronics case chain mount coming off with it.

All of the wires to your print head will need to be lengthened in order to use this drag chain. I cut my wires, soldered a piece in and insulated them with heat shrink.

I printed my chain with black PLA and the photo does not show the best detail. It was taken before I lengthened and installed the wires in it.

description.text:
These clips attach to a hat, headband, or wig to elevate the supply lines of an over-the-ear nasal cannula above the ear and prevent or alleviate abrasion and ulceration.

Patients undergoing respiratory therapy often receive oxygen via thin flexible tubing and a small device that is inserted into the nostrils. The tubing sits between the patient's head and the tops of the ears and can cause small sores on the ears. In the best cases, the sores are irritating and short term. In extreme cases, the ulcers can be very slow to heal and become infected.

These clips were developed for a family member who suffered from painful skin ulcers aggravated by his oxygen lines. The relief was immediate and allowed his skin to heal and be comfortable. The clips fit a variety of caps and hats, fabric/elastic headbands, and would even be suitable to attach to a wig.

Sadly, we lost Oscar on September 1, 2017. These clips are being published in his memory. If you have a loved one, a patient, a friend, or a neighbor who needs relief from their ears being rubbed raw, by all means print up a pair of airhose clips for them.

There are four designs to choose from. We settled on the D version since it has a flat profile and held the airhose well, even when worn while lying down sideways. Version A is shown in the photograph. B and C are similarly functional, just styled differently.

Introduction

Replacement Filament guides for E3D Titan.

I was having problems printing flexible filaments, with the filament getting squeezed past the hob gear and bunching up. This was caused by the excessive clearance between the injection molded PTFE guide and the gear. The stock components have a 0.4mm gap between the guide and the hobbed gear. This is 25% of the filament's thickness and easily enough space for the filament to be forced through (when that filament is NinjaFlex!)

I have designed these guides to reduce that clearance down to almost zero and to bring the PTFE tube right up to the gear.

So far this has done the trick, but I will keep you updated with any new developments (see updates).

Printing

The part is available with a 4.1, 4.2 and 4.3mm hole in the middle, so you can choose the one which prints best on your printer to fit your PTFE tube (4.2 was best on mine).
I printed them at 0.1mm layer height on my modified CR-10

Update 1:

This part does a great job of constraining the filament as it leaves the hobbed gear, but I am now having problems with the filament moving to the side before it arrives at the hobbed gear, causing it to bunch up. I will be designing a piece to go between the idler and the top of the hobbed gear. Stay tuned for more information....

comments.text: It didn't work out of the box, but I totally expected to do some slicing and dicing to make everything work together.  The filament guide on the Aero actually sits on a little platform on the heat sink, and the assembled heat sink then needs to mount to the plastic Titan body in the normal fashion where the filament guide base has its own channel and the heat sink assembly then snaps into the frame.  As such, the depth of the base is critical to the fitment of the heat sink into the body.  I could tell by looking at your prints that this would have to be modified as you print would put the heat sink much lower than the frame needs. :)  So I printed the 4.2 and measured a platform of 1.90mm.  The stock one was around 1.60mm so I needed to shave .30mm off the platform.  Also, the PTFE tube didn't even come close to fitting so I modified the 4.3 version of the guide in Fusion 360 to remove the .30mm off the base.  Printed the modified one and that base was close enough.  The PTFE tube still wasn't going to fit so I drilled the whole pathway using a 4mm drill bit and then used a 3/16" drill bit to open up the bottom of the holde upwards until the 3/16' hole was just below the area where the guide started opening up for the gear fitment. This allowed me to feed the PTFE tube pretty freely from the bottom and get the 4mm holding resistance at the top of the guide.  Initial fitment was good and all I needed was some deft xacto knifing to sculpt the PTFE and the filament guide to get that perfect fit at the gears.

This is a printable plastic plate used to mount an aluminum angle iron to the Trinus X carraige so as to be able to mount a Flexion Extruder.

Anyone who owns a Kodama Trinus eventually gets fed up with the stock extruder. Although reasonably capable, it's enclosed design encourages heat creep and clogging. Many owners have adapted the E3D extruder. I decided I would prefer the Flexion for its unparalleled ability to print flexible filaments.

The pictures are accurate if a bit misleading. They show an earlier iteration with a longer aluminum bracket. I found the longer bracket used too much z axis height, so I shortened it. The principals and directions are the same, but your finished product will look slightly different. There is also a cooling fan mount not shown, which I added later. The file is here for that as well. The fan mount is screwed into the X axis plate using longer 3mm screws to go through the fan mount and then the extruder mounting plate and into the two threaded holes on the top of the X carraige.

To use this plate you will also need a two inch wide, 2" x 2" aluminum angle. On one side of the angle you will need to drill two 4mm holes to allow two M3 screws into the tapped mounting holes on the bottom of the cold block. You will also need to drill a 10 mm hole to allow the throat through the aluminum angle.

The back of the plastic plate has countersunk holes for tapered head 6 mm M3 screws. You will need to drill corresponding holes into the other side of the the aluminum angle, and thread those holes with an M3 .5 mm tap.

comments.text: The holes on the back plate you uploaded don't fit with the holes on the front plate. I should have overlapped the parts in the slicer before printing!  Oops!   You're getting very close on the front plate though.   On the front plate,  the two top screw holes (the ones farther from the edge) need to be about 3.8mm closer to the bottom screw holes to match up with the holes on the board.   The hole for the knob needs to be about 6mm lower and about 4mm closer to the screen.   The distance between the screw holes on the board vertically should be about 50.75mm     Other than getting that screw spacing perfect, and the knob placement,  the front is good to go.    Two things I could suggest to make your life easier on this one:   For the cutout on the back panel for the cords,  I've yet to have one of these that was an exact fit.  Maybe just make that hole quite a bit bigger to make measurement errors matter less.  Nobody is going to see that side anyway.    And on the front,  make the hole for the knob about half the size it currently is.  It only needs to be big enough for the post for the knob to fit through, and that way you're not in a situation where being off by 2 mm shows a crescent moon of empty space around the knob.  Don't give up, you're getting really close.    I like the decision to go down to 5mm for the holes for the mount pivots since it lets people use M5 Screws.   If you want to get fancy, you could include a file for 4.9mm diameter dowels people could print if they don't have an appropriate sized screw.
